# 📊 Market Sentiment vs Trader Behavior Analysis

## 🔍 Project Overview
This project investigates the relationship between market sentiment (Fear vs Greed) and trader behavior using BTC/USD minute-level OHLCV data. It focuses on how sentiment influences trading decisions, risk-taking, and overall profitability.

---

## ⚙️ Methodology
- Performed data cleaning and preprocessing on a corrupted dataset
- Engineered key features including price returns, trading volume, and volatility
- Developed a composite sentiment score to classify market phases (Fear vs Greed)
- Simulated realistic trader behavior based on market conditions:
  - Position sizing
  - Leverage usage
  - Trade direction (Long/Short)
- Conducted statistical analysis using hypothesis testing (T-test)

---

## 📊 Key Findings
- Fear-phase trading showed slightly higher average profitability compared to Greed phases
- Higher leverage was associated with increased volatility and reduced win rate
- Trader discipline and risk management had a greater impact on outcomes than market sentiment alone

---

## 🛠 Tech Stack
- Python
- Pandas & NumPy
- Matplotlib & Seaborn
- SciPy (Statistical Testing)

---

## 📂 Project Structure
- `market_sentiment_analysis.ipynb` — Main analysis notebook
- `data.csv` — Input dataset

---

## 🚀 Conclusion
The study highlights that while market sentiment provides contextual signals, trader behavior—particularly leverage control and position management—plays a more critical role in determining profitability.

